review_blob:
Cinnamon, clove, maple, brown sugar, aggressive pumpkin, light vegetal flavor. The hops are present, but take a serious backseat. Light color, and a surprisingly thin mouthfeel. Masterfully done. This is how a pumpkin beer should be brewed.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Nose is woody and lightly spiced. If there's any maple here, it's in the aroma, and its almost indistinguishable. Luckily, it's also a solid brew. The taste is white pepper, oak bark, a touch of cinnamon, clove, and an aggressive piney dryness. This is much hoppier than its countenance lets on. The bittering hops are assertive and absolutely do not quit. There's a ghost of a sweetness on the very end hiding under the hop storm that could be the maple, but could well be just caramel malts. The finish is just drier than Bakersfield. I'd drink it again.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob:
Lemon, coriander, kalamata olive, grass, straw, fruity esters peeking through. Rustic, musty backbone. Fizzy, but sticks around on the tongue. Finish is arid. Outstanding.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

A black IPA that is still an IPA. It's far less contrived and ham handed than many other examples out there. It still has the grassy bite and subtle fruity hints of a west coast IPA, but the malt backbone is rich and bold. The dark flavors are ashy and woody. The mouthfeel is medium. Very little head and a light but respectable degree of lacing. All the while I got the feeling that this was truly to style rather than a DIPA/porter mash up. Confident, phenomenal, sexual beer.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Stone Sublimely Self Righteous Black IPA

review_blob:
Aggressive, rude, abrasive. Mouthfeel like thick whole milk. Piney, rustic aroma. Unapologetic hop assault. Flavor is toffee, white pepper, and very slight lemon and pineapple. Finish is dry as dust with a little soapiness. Lacing absolutely does not quit. This is a good beer, probably a great beer, but I wouldn't use the word "enjoyable". It most certainly is what it is.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Wow, this is a really nice brew. Deep red color. This isnt nearly as dark as I was expecting. Very strong, bold, dried fruits with nuts, mild roots, and wood. Very light soy sauce. I mean barely perceptible. Almost hints at being Belgian, but its not. Imagine a Belgian strong ale, with some some of the yeast cut back. The alcohol comes through, but not really representative of how high the ABV is. This is a really complex beer. Feels nice on the palate, too. Its got a little skin to it, if you know what I mean. Only complaint is its like thirteen bucks for (I think) 18oz. Its good, but I dont know about thirteen dollars good.

Great aroma. Hops jump right out; citrus and floral scents dominate. Very nice color for how wispy and fizzy this beer is. Its a deeper amber than one would expect given the taste and palate. Overall palate is alright. Kind of thin and transient, but the dry hoppy bite stays behind. This beer is very dry. The taste is absolutely oppressive grass and floral. The citrus is lemon. Theres almost a raw celery taste there or something. Its a really harsh, green, leafy flavor. I cant believe the ABV is this low. Nice color, fantastic aroma, but I really didnt like the flavor of this beer very much--not particularly refreshing. Too dry, too grassy, too harsh, just too much for claiming to be a very sessionable beer.
beer_name: Ballast Point / Kelsey McNair / Stone San Diego County Session Ale

review_blob: I loved this barleywine. Its sweet, but I like a real sweet brew from time to time. Its a nice dark brown, with a full body and thick mouthfeel. The aroma leaves something to be desired; thats where the alcohol makes itself known. The first taste Is caramel, fig, toasted nut, and a dull orange flavor (not tangy.) As I progress through the beer, theres more coffee there. I didnt find the finish very dry at all. Its a pretty sticky brew the whole way through. Its highly drinkable/enjoyable, and despite the fairly high ABV, I never felt like I was getting my ass kicked. Fantastic.
beer_name: Marin Old Dipsea Barleywine Style Ale

review_blob: Bam! Orange and lemon peel punch to the nostrils. Quite pungent citrus aroma, with a touch of yeast, obviously. First sip was a little surprising; this brew is a thinner body than I was expecting. Not weak and tenuous or anything, but I was expecting a thicker feel. After the citrus and yeast, the brew is grassy and floral. Make no mistake, this beer is Californian before Belgian. The only thing I wasnt impressed with was the appearance. Decent head that recesses into a bit of lace, but the color is a real unassuming, light amber color. But you know, who cares, its a beer, not a mural. Delicious brew, and worth the price of the bomber. Nothing breathtaking, but tasty.
